\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Identity is 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{n}=1$
\end_inset

, the inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{p}=\theta^{-p}=\theta^{n-p}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In such a group 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is called generating element
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Any element 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{p}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 are relatively prime, is again a generating element 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Integers under addition modulo 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 form a group, which is isomorphic to the previous one.
 Identical group structures can be realized in different ways.
 A group which is generated by a single element 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 which satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{n}=e$
\end_inset

 is called cyclic group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In some sense most general finite group is the 
\emph on
symmetric 
\emph default
group 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n},$
\end_inset

consisting of the permutation of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 things.
 Cayley's theorem states that every finite group of order 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{N}$
\end_inset

.
 This group is not Abelian
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Infinite discrete groups
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{Z},+)$
\end_inset

: Integer numbers under addition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Modular 
\emph default
group of 
\begin_inset Formula $SL(2,\mathbb{Z})$
\end_inset

 of integer-values 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 matrices with unit determinant, under matrix multiplication.
 Important in string theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

