\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 together with a topology on 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 such that the group's binary operation (group product) and group's inverse
 function are continuous functions with respect to the topology.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Orthogonal 
\emph default
group 
\begin_inset Formula $O(n)$
\end_inset

, the group of real 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $O^{T}O=I$
\end_inset

.
 This corresponds to rotations and reflections in 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-dimensional Euclidean space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 The topology of the group is the subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $O(n)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n\times n}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Unitary
\emph default
 group 
\begin_inset Formula $U(m)$
\end_inset

, the group of complex 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrices satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{\dagger}U=I$
\end_inset

.
 This corresponds to (holomorphic) rotations and reflections in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}^{n}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Orthogonal matrices have determinant 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset

, while unitary matrices have determinant 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\varphi}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 modulus one.
 In both cases, there is a 
\emph on
special 
\emph default
version of the groups, 
\begin_inset Formula $SO(n)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(n)$
\end_inset

, respectively, with the extra distraction that the matrices must have determina
nt one
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Orthogonal groups are not connected: The determinant is a continuous function
 of the group elements, and since it can only take values 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $O(n)$
\end_inset

 must have (at least) two connected components, one of which is 
\begin_inset Formula $SO(n)$
\end_inset

, while matrices with determinant 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 do not form a group
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Unclear
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

