Continuous non compact groups
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The real (rational, complex) numbers under addition.
 If zero is excluded, they also form a group under multiplication 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Subgroups 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a subset of elements which forms a group under the group product of
 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Every subgroup must contain the identity 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A subset 
\begin_inset Formula $H\subset G$
\end_inset

 is a subgroup if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall\,h_{1},h_{2}\in H,\,h_{1}h_{2}^{-1}\in H$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This has to be because a group must fulfill 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{2}^{-1}\in H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}h_{j}\in H$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\{e\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 itself are trivial subgroups
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is Abelian, so is 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 The converse is not true
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Every element 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 generates an Abelian subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $\{g\}$
\end_inset

.
 For elements of finite order, we simply have 
\begin_inset Formula $g=\{g^{p}\},\,p=1,\,\ldots,\,\text{ord}\,g$
\end_inset


\end_layout

