\begin_layout Subsection*
Normal Subgroups
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A subgroup is called a normal subgroup (or invariant subgroup) if it is
 self-conjugate, i.e.
 if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
gHg^{-1}=H\quad\forall\,g\in G
\]

\end_inset

This is denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $H\triangleleft G$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A normal subgroup is one for which left and right cosets coincide, since
 
\begin_inset Formula $gHg^{-1}=H\Leftrightarrow gH=Hg$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A normal subgroup must be a union of conjugacy classes 
\begin_inset Formula $[g]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}=ghg^{-1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For Abelian groups, every subgroup is normal 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Since all 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 commute, 
\begin_inset Formula $gH=Hg$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
gHg^{-1}=H
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The center (elements which commute with all elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

) is always a normal subgroup 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A subgroup which contains half of all elements, i.e.
 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\bigl|G\bigr|=2\bigl|H\bigr|$
\end_inset

 is a normal subgroup 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Why?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
gH\in H\quad\forall\,g\in H
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

