\begin_layout Subsection*
Quotient Groups 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Normal or invariant subgroups allow for the construction of quotient groups.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is a normal subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Loosely speaking, quotient group 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H$
\end_inset

 is obtained by dividing out the subgroup
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $H\vartriangleleft G$
\end_inset

 (be a normal subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

).
 The quotient group is the set of left cosets of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G/H=\{gH\bigl|g\in G\}
\]

\end_inset

The group operation is defined as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g_{1}H\cdot g_{2}H=g_{1}g_{2}H
\]

\end_inset

Group elements 
\begin_inset Formula $g\neq g'$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $gH=g'H$
\end_inset

, make sure replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $g'$
\end_inset

 leads to the same result
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 itself is the identity element since 
\begin_inset Formula $H\cdot gH=gH$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $H=hH\quad\forall\,h\in H$
