 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{w_{a}\}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 A basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is then given by the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{v_{i}\otimes w_{a}\}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V=\{a^{ia}v_{i}\otimes w_{a}\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{ia}$
\end_inset

 depending on whether 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{2}$
\end_inset

 are real or complex spaces.
 Implicit sum convention 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a^{ia}v_{i}\otimes\,w_{a}=\sum_{i=1}^{d_{1}}\sum_{a=1}^{d_{2}}a^{ia}v_{i}\otimes\,w_{a}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
An elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}$
\end_inset

 is thus specified by its components 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{ia}$
\end_inset

 which can be pictured as a matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a^{ia}=\begin{pmatrix}a^{11} &  & a^{1d_{2}}\\
\\
a^{d_{1}1} &  & a^{d_{1}d_{2}}
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Basis elements of the tensor product space are products of the basis elements
 of the factors, a general element 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}\otimes V_{2}$
\end_inset

 cannot be written as a single tensor product of an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}$
\end_inset

 and an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In QM, this is called entanglement.
 Simples form, two spins which can be either up or down.
 Then an entangled state would be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bigl|\uparrow\bigr\rangle_{1}\otimes\bigl|\uparrow\bigr\rangle_{2}-\bigl|\uparrow\bigr\rangle_{1}\otimes\bigl|\uparrow\bigr\rangle_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Schur's Lemma
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Important property for irreducible components (subspace representations).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Definition
\series default
: Given two representations 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{2}$
\end_inset

 on acting on 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{2}$
\end_inset

m an inter-winer between 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{2}$
\end_inset

 is a linear operator which 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

commutes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F:\,V_{1}\mapsto V_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
FD_{1}(g)=D_{2}(g)F\quad\forall\,g\in G
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Kernel and image of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 are invariant subspaces.
 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in\text{ker}F$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Fv=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
FD_{1}v=D_{2}Fv=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
So 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{1}v\in\text{ker}F$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Eigenstates in QM
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Eigenstates of the Hamiltonian for a given energy come in (usually irreducible)
 representations of the symmetry group
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Consider symmetry group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 of the Hamiltonian, i.e.
 those operators which commute with 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Divide Hilbert space into the eigenspaces of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 the subspaces corresponding to the different eigenvalues
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Each such subspace carries a representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, since acting with any 
\begin_inset Formula $D(g)$
\end_inset

 does not change the eigenvalue, because
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[H,\,D(g)]=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Because Hilbert space is a complex vector space
\end_layout

